answer:
`useState` is a built-in Hook that lets a function component hold state across renders. Calling it returns a pair: the current state value and a setter that schedules an update and triggers a re-render.

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

A few things worth knowing:
- The argument to `useState` is the initial value, used only on the first render. If computing it is expensive, pass a function (`useState(() => expensiveInit())`) so it runs only once.
- State updates are asynchronous and batched. If the next value depends on the previous one, prefer the functional form: `setCount(prev => prev + 1)`.
- Setting state to the same value (by `Object.is` comparison) bails out and skips the re-render.
- Each call to `useState` is an independent slot of state. Keep them at the top level of the component so React can match them up by call order across renders.

JSX (JavaScript XML) is a syntax extension that lets you write HTML-like markup inside JavaScript. It is not required to use React, but almost every React codebase uses it because it is more readable than raw `createElement` calls.

Under the hood, a build tool (Babel, SWC, esbuild, TypeScript) compiles JSX into calls to React's element factory. The two snippets below produce the same element tree:

Without JSX:
```js
const text = React.createElement('p', null, 'This is a text');
const container = React.createElement('div', null, text);
ReactDOM.render(container, rootElement);
```

With JSX:
```jsx
const container = (
  <div>
    <p>This is a text</p>
  </div>
);
ReactDOM.render(container, rootElement);
```

A few JSX details worth knowing:
- Attributes use camelCase: `className` (not `class`), `onClick` (not `onclick`), `htmlFor` (not `for`).
- You can embed any JavaScript expression with curly braces: `<p>Hello, {user.name}</p>`.
- A component must return a single root node. Use a fragment (`<>...</>`) when you don't want an extra wrapper element.
- The modern automatic JSX runtime (React 17+) means you no longer need `import React from 'react'` in every file just to use JSX.

Before Hooks (React 16.8), function components were stateless and lifecycle-free, so class components were the only option for anything beyond rendering props. Since Hooks, function components have feature parity with classes and are the recommended default for new code.

Declaration

Function components are plain JavaScript functions that return JSX:

```jsx
function Card(props) {
  return (
    <div className="main-container">
      <h2>Title of the card</h2>
    </div>
  );
}

const Card = (props) => (
  <div className="main-container">
    <h2>Title of the card</h2>
  </div>
);
```

Class components use the ES6 class syntax and extend `React.Component`:

```jsx
class Card extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return (
      <div className="main-container">
        <h2>Title of the card</h2>
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

Handling props

In a function component, props are just the function's argument:

```jsx
function StudentInfo(props) {
  return (
    <div className="main">
      <h2>{props.name}</h2>
      <h4>{props.rollNumber}</h4>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In a class component, props live on the instance and are accessed via `this.props`:

```jsx
class StudentInfo extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return (
      <div className="main">
        <h2>{this.props.name}</h2>
        <h4>{this.props.rollNumber}</h4>
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

Handling state

Function components use the `useState` Hook:

```jsx
function ClassRoom() {
  const [studentsCount, setStudentsCount] = useState(0);
  const addStudent = () => setStudentsCount(c => c + 1);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Number of students: {studentsCount}</p>
      <button onClick={addStudent}>Add Student</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Class components keep state on the instance and update it with `setState`:

```jsx
class ClassRoom extends React.Component {
  state = { studentsCount: 0 };

  addStudent = () => {
    this.setState(prev => ({ studentsCount: prev.studentsCount + 1 }));
  };

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <p>Number of students: {this.state.studentsCount}</p>
        <button onClick={this.addStudent}>Add Student</button>
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

Other practical differences:
- Function components compose behavior with Hooks; class components use lifecycle methods (`componentDidMount`, `componentDidUpdate`, `componentWillUnmount`).
- Function components don't have a `this`, which removes a whole class of binding bugs.
- Class components must manually bind handlers (or use class fields/arrow methods) to keep `this` correct.
- All current React features (concurrent rendering, Suspense, server components) are designed around function components.

Controlled and uncontrolled refer to two ways of handling form input in React.

| Capability | Uncontrolled | Controlled |
| --- | --- | --- |
| One-time value retrieval (e.g. on submit) | yes | yes |
| Validating on submit | yes | yes |
| Field-level validation | no | yes |
| Conditionally disabling the submit button | no | yes |
| Enforcing a specific input format | no | yes |
| Combining several inputs into one piece of data | no | yes |
| Dynamic inputs | no | yes |

Controlled component

The value of the input is stored in React state. Every keystroke triggers `onChange`, which updates state and re-renders the input with the new value. React is the single source of truth.

```jsx
function FormValidation() {
  const [inputValue, setInputValue] = useState('');

  return (
    <form>
      <input
        type="text"
        value={inputValue}
        onChange={e => setInputValue(e.target.value)}
      />
    </form>
  );
}
```

Uncontrolled component

The DOM keeps the value itself; React doesn't track each keystroke. You read the value when you need it, typically via a ref.

```jsx
function FormValidation() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    alert(`Input value: ${inputRef.current.value}`);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input type="text" ref={inputRef} defaultValue="" />
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

When to use which:
- Use controlled inputs when you need to validate, format, or react to each change.
- Use uncontrolled inputs (or libraries built on them like React Hook Form) when forms are large and you want to avoid a re-render per keystroke.

Props (short for "properties") are the inputs to a React component. A parent passes data and callbacks to a child via JSX attributes, and the child receives them as a single object.

```jsx
<Element reactProp="1" />
```

Inside a function component, props arrive as the first argument:

```jsx
function Element(props) {
  return <p>{props.reactProp}</p>;
}
```

Inside a class component, they live on `this.props`:

```jsx
class Element extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <p>{this.props.reactProp}</p>;
  }
}
```

Important points about props:
- They are read-only. A component must not mutate the props it receives. To request a change, call a callback prop the parent provided.
- They can be any JavaScript value: primitives, objects, arrays, functions, or even other React elements (`children`).
- The special `children` prop holds whatever JSX you nest inside a component's tags.
- Default values can be supplied with destructuring (`function Element({ reactProp = '1' })`) or, for class components, the `defaultProps` static field.

State and props are the two ways data flows into a component, but they serve different roles.

State

State is data a component owns and manages itself. Changing state schedules a re-render. In class components, state lives on `this.state` and is updated with `setState`. In function components, state is created with `useState` (or `useReducer` for complex logic).

Class component example:

```jsx
class Car extends React.Component {
  state = { brand: 'BMW', color: 'Black' };

  changeColor = () => {
    this.setState({ color: 'Red' });
  };

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <button onClick={this.changeColor}>Change Color</button>
        <p>{this.state.color}</p>
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

The equivalent function component:

```jsx
function Car() {
  const [color, setColor] = useState('Black');

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setColor('Red')}>Change Color</button>
      <p>{color}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Props

Props are inputs passed in from the parent. The component receives them and renders accordingly, but cannot modify them.

```jsx
<Car brand="Mercedes" />
```

```jsx
function Car(props) {
  return <p>Brand: {props.brand}</p>;
}
```

Quick comparison:
- State is owned and mutated by the component; props are owned by the parent and read by the child.
- Both trigger re-renders when they change.
- A common pattern is "lift state up": move shared state to a common ancestor and pass it down as props.

In React, "side effects" are anything a component does besides computing JSX from props and state — fetching data, subscribing to events, updating the document title, working with timers, manipulating the DOM directly, and so on. They're managed with the `useEffect` Hook (or class lifecycle methods).

There are two flavors:

Effects without cleanup

These run after render and don't need to be undone. Examples include logging, sending an analytics event, or updating the document title.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  document.title = `Hello, ${name}`;
}, [name]);
```

Effects with cleanup

These set up something that must be torn down when the component unmounts or before the effect runs again — subscriptions, event listeners, intervals, WebSocket connections. Return a cleanup function from the effect; React calls it on unmount and before re-running the effect.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => tick(), 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, []);
```

Without the cleanup you'd leak timers, listeners, or sockets every time the component re-renders or unmounts.

Error boundaries are React components that catch JavaScript errors thrown anywhere in their child component tree during rendering, in lifecycle methods, and in constructors. They render a fallback UI instead of crashing the whole app. Introduced in React 16.

What they do not catch:
- Errors inside event handlers (use a regular `try/catch`).
- Errors in asynchronous code (e.g. `setTimeout` callbacks or promise rejections).
- Errors thrown in the error boundary itself.
- Server-side rendering errors.

A component becomes an error boundary by implementing `static getDerivedStateFromError` (to update state and render a fallback) and/or `componentDidCatch` (to log the error). Error boundaries currently exist only as class components.

```jsx
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = { hasError: false };

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    return { hasError: true };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error, errorInfo) {
    logErrorToMyService(error, errorInfo);
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      return <h4>Something went wrong.</h4>;
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

Wrap any subtree you want to isolate:

```jsx
<ErrorBoundary>
  <CounterComponent />
</ErrorBoundary>
```

A common pattern is to place error boundaries around independent parts of the UI (sidebar, main content, widget) so a failure in one area doesn't take down the whole page.

Hooks are functions that let you "hook into" React state and lifecycle features from function components. They cannot be used in class components.

Why they exist

Before Hooks, function components were stateless. Any component that needed state, lifecycle methods, or refs had to be rewritten as a class. That led to common pain points: hard-to-reuse stateful logic (Higher-Order Components and render props made the tree deeply nested), giant lifecycle methods that mixed unrelated logic, and confusion around `this`. Hooks fix this by:
- Letting function components own state and side effects directly.
- Letting you extract and share stateful logic via custom Hooks.
- Grouping related logic together (e.g. the subscribe and unsubscribe of an effect live in the same `useEffect`).

Example of `useState`:

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';

function Person() {
  const [name, setName] = useState('');

  return (
    <input
      value={name}
      onChange={e => setName(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}
```

The state variable `name` can be used directly inside the JSX and updated with `setName`.

`useEffect` lets a function component run side effects — data fetching, subscriptions, document title updates, manual DOM mutations, timers — after the component renders. It is the function-component counterpart to lifecycle methods like `componentDidMount`, `componentDidUpdate`, and `componentWillUnmount`.

Signature:

```js
useEffect(callback, dependencies?);
```

- `callback` runs after the DOM has been updated. It can optionally return a cleanup function.
- `dependencies` is an array of values the effect depends on. The effect re-runs only when one of them changes.

Behavior based on the dependency array:
- No array: the effect runs after every render.
- Empty array `[]`: the effect runs once, after the first render, and the cleanup runs on unmount.
- Array with values: the effect runs on mount and whenever any listed value changes.

Example:

```jsx
import { useEffect } from 'react';

function WelcomeGreetings({ name }) {
  const msg = `Hi, ${name}!`;

  useEffect(() => {
    document.title = `Welcome, ${name}`;
  }, [name]);

  return <div>{msg}</div>;
}
```

Without `[name]` in the dependency array, the title would be re-set on every render. With it, the update happens only when `name` changes.

Tip: include every value from component scope that the effect uses. The `react-hooks/exhaustive-deps` ESLint rule will warn you about missed dependencies.

Refs let a component hold onto a value that persists across renders without triggering a re-render when it changes. The `useRef` Hook brought that capability to function components (refs were previously available only on class instances via `createRef`).

Common uses for refs:
- Accessing a DOM node imperatively: managing focus, text selection, scroll position, or media playback.
- Integrating with non-React DOM libraries (charts, maps, rich-text editors).
- Triggering imperative animations.
- Storing any mutable value that should not cause a re-render when it changes (e.g. a previous value, a timer id, or a flag).

Example:

```jsx
function TextInput() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    inputRef.current.focus();
  }, []);

  return <input ref={inputRef} />;
}
```

`inputRef.current` is the DOM node after the component mounts. Mutating `.current` does not schedule a render, which is the whole point: refs are an escape hatch for values that live outside React's render-driven data flow.

A custom Hook is a JavaScript function whose name starts with `use` and that calls other Hooks. It lets you extract stateful logic from a component so it can be reused, without changing the component hierarchy.

Example: a Hook that tracks whether the user is online.

```jsx
function useOnlineStatus() {
  const [isOnline, setIsOnline] = useState(navigator.onLine);

  useEffect(() => {
    const update = () => setIsOnline(navigator.onLine);
    window.addEventListener('online', update);
    window.addEventListener('offline', update);
    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener('online', update);
      window.removeEventListener('offline', update);
    };
  }, []);

  return isOnline;
}

function StatusBar() {
  const isOnline = useOnlineStatus();
  return <p>{isOnline ? 'Online' : 'Offline'}</p>;
}
```

Why they help:
- Reuse logic across components without the nesting that Higher-Order Components and render props cause.
- Keep components focused on rendering; move the "how" of state and effects into Hooks.
- Each component that uses the Hook gets its own independent state — Hooks share logic, not state.

Limitation: like all Hooks, they cannot be used inside class components.

`StrictMode` is a development-only tool, added in React 16.3, that helps surface potential problems in an application. It produces no visible UI and has no effect in production builds.

Wrap part (or all) of the tree in `<React.StrictMode>` to enable the extra checks:

```jsx
import { StrictMode } from 'react';
import { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client';
import App from './App';

const root = createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(
  <StrictMode>
    <App />
  </StrictMode>
);
```

What StrictMode currently checks:
- Warns about components that use unsafe lifecycle methods (`componentWillMount`, `componentWillReceiveProps`, `componentWillUpdate`).
- Warns about the legacy string `ref` API; recommends callback or `createRef` refs instead.
- Warns about uses of `findDOMNode`, which is deprecated.
- Warns about the legacy Context API (`childContextTypes`, `getChildContext`).
- Detects unexpected side effects by intentionally invoking certain functions twice in development (constructors, render methods, `useState`/`useReducer` initializers, and effects in React 18+). If your code is purely a function of its inputs, double-invocation has no visible effect; if it has hidden side effects, they become obvious.

Treat StrictMode as a development aid that pushes you toward idiomatic, side-effect-free render code.

A component re-renders when its state or props change, or when a parent re-renders (so its children re-render by default). Unnecessary re-renders waste CPU and can make the UI feel sluggish.

Common ways to reduce them:

`React.memo` for function components

`React.memo` wraps a component and skips re-rendering if its props are shallow-equal to the previous render.

```jsx
const Message = React.memo(function Message({ text }) {
  console.log('Message rendered');
  return <p>{text}</p>;
});
```

`PureComponent` and `shouldComponentUpdate` for class components

`React.PureComponent` does a shallow comparison of props and state and skips the update if nothing changed. For full control, implement `shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps, nextState)` and return `false` to skip the render.

```jsx
class Message extends React.PureComponent {
  render() {
    return <p>{this.props.text}</p>;
  }
}
```

Stabilize props with `useMemo` and `useCallback`

`React.memo` only helps if the props are referentially stable. Wrap object/array props with `useMemo` and function props with `useCallback` so they keep the same reference between renders when their inputs haven't changed.

```jsx
const options = useMemo(() => ({ sort: 'asc' }), []);
const handleClick = useCallback(() => doThing(id), [id]);
```

Other practical guidance:
- Keep state as local as possible. State that lives high in the tree forces every component below it to re-render.
- Split big components so that the parts that change often don't drag the parts that rarely change along with them.
- For long lists, use virtualization (react-window, react-virtualized) so only the visible rows render.
- Don't reach for memoization until you've measured. The React DevTools Profiler is the best way to see which components are re-rendering and why.

There are several common ways to style a React component; most teams pick one or two that fit their project.

Inline styles

Pass a JavaScript object to the `style` prop. Useful for one-off dynamic values, but lacks features like pseudo-classes and media queries.

```jsx
function RandomComponent() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h3 style={{ color: 'yellow' }}>This is a heading</h3>
      <p style={{ fontSize: '32px' }}>This is a paragraph</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Style object reuse

Declare a JavaScript object once and reuse it across elements.

```jsx
const paragraphStyles = { color: 'red', fontSize: '32px' };
const headingStyles = { color: 'blue', fontSize: '48px' };

function RandomComponent() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h3 style={headingStyles}>This is a heading</h3>
      <p style={paragraphStyles}>This is a paragraph</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Plain CSS stylesheets

Write traditional CSS files and import them. Class names are global, so you need a convention (BEM, etc.) to avoid collisions.

```jsx
import './RandomComponent.css';

function RandomComponent() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h3 className="heading">This is a heading</h3>
      <p className="paragraph">This is a paragraph</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

CSS Modules

Files named `*.module.css` are imported as objects with locally scoped class names, which prevents collisions.

```css
/* styles.module.css */
.paragraph {
  color: red;
  border: 1px solid black;
}
```

```jsx
import styles from './styles.module.css';

function RandomComponent() {
  return <p className={styles.paragraph}>This is a paragraph</p>;
}
```

CSS-in-JS

Libraries like styled-components and Emotion let you co-locate styles with components and use props to drive them.

```jsx
import styled from 'styled-components';

const Heading = styled.h3`
  color: blue;
  font-size: 48px;
`;
```

Utility-first CSS

Tailwind CSS applies styles via utility class names directly in JSX.

```jsx
<h3 className="text-blue-600 text-5xl">This is a heading</h3>
```

There is no single best choice — pick based on team familiarity, build setup, and how dynamic the styling needs to be.

A few common patterns, depending on the relationship between the components:

Parent to child: pass props

```jsx
import ChildComponent from './Child';

function ParentComponent() {
  const [counter, setCounter] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setCounter(c => c + 1)}>Increment</button>
      <ChildComponent counterValue={counter} />
    </div>
  );
}

function ChildComponent({ counterValue }) {
  return <p>Value of counter: {counterValue}</p>;
}
```

Child to parent: callback props

The parent passes a callback down; the child invokes it with the data it wants to send up.

```jsx
function ParentComponent() {
  const [counter, setCounter] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Value of counter: {counter}</p>
      <ChildComponent value={counter} onChange={setCounter} />
    </div>
  );
}

function ChildComponent({ value, onChange }) {
  return (
    <button onClick={() => onChange(value + 1)}>Increment</button>
  );
}
```

Sibling components: lift state up

Move the shared state into the nearest common ancestor and pass it down (and pass setters down) as props.

Distant components: Context or a state library

When data needs to be available to many components across the tree, use:
- `React.createContext` + `useContext` for app-wide values like theme, auth, or locale.
- A state-management library (Redux, Zustand, Jotai, Recoil) for larger global state.
- A server-state library (TanStack Query, SWR) for data that originates from a backend.

A Higher-Order Component (HOC) is a function that takes a component and returns a new component, typically to share behavior across many components. It's a pattern, not a built-in React feature.

When you'd reach for one

You have several components that need the same behavior — say, subscribing to a data source and re-rendering when it changes. Duplicating that lifecycle code in each component is wasteful. A HOC lets you write the logic once.

Two components with duplicated subscription logic:

```jsx
class ArticlesList extends React.Component {
  state = { articles: GlobalDataSource.getArticles() };
  handleChange = () => this.setState({ articles: GlobalDataSource.getArticles() });
  componentDidMount() { GlobalDataSource.addChangeListener(this.handleChange); }
  componentWillUnmount() { GlobalDataSource.removeChangeListener(this.handleChange); }
  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        {this.state.articles.map(a => <ArticleData article={a} key={a.id} />)}
      </div>
    );
  }
}

class UsersList extends React.Component {
  state = { users: GlobalDataSource.getUsers() };
  handleChange = () => this.setState({ users: GlobalDataSource.getUsers() });
  componentDidMount() { GlobalDataSource.addChangeListener(this.handleChange); }
  componentWillUnmount() { GlobalDataSource.removeChangeListener(this.handleChange); }
  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        {this.state.users.map(u => <UserData user={u} key={u.id} />)}
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

Extracting the shared logic into a HOC:

```jsx
function withSubscription(WrappedComponent, selectData) {
  return class extends React.Component {
    state = { data: selectData(GlobalDataSource, this.props) };
    handleChange = () => this.setState({ data: selectData(GlobalDataSource, this.props) });
    componentDidMount() { GlobalDataSource.addChangeListener(this.handleChange); }
    componentWillUnmount() { GlobalDataSource.removeChangeListener(this.handleChange); }
    render() {
      return <WrappedComponent data={this.state.data} {...this.props} />;
    }
  };
}

const ArticlesListWithSub = withSubscription(ArticlesList, ds => ds.getArticles());
const UsersListWithSub = withSubscription(UsersList, ds => ds.getUsers());
```

Modern guidance: in new code, custom Hooks are usually a cleaner solution than HOCs for the same problem. HOCs add wrapper components to the tree and can make prop forwarding awkward; custom Hooks share logic without changing the component hierarchy.

Conditional rendering means showing different UI based on the current state, just like normal JavaScript conditions decide which branch of code runs. React doesn't have a special template syntax for it — you use plain JS inside JSX.

Common patterns:

`if` / `else` (often in a helper or early return):

```jsx
function Greeting({ isLoggedIn, user }) {
  if (isLoggedIn) {
    return <h1>Welcome back, {user.name}!</h1>;
  }
  return <h1>Please sign in.</h1>;
}
```

Ternary expressions for short branches inside JSX:

```jsx
<p>{isOnline ? 'Online' : 'Offline'}</p>
```

Logical AND for "render this only when":

```jsx
{unreadCount > 0 && <Badge>{unreadCount}</Badge>}
```

(Use a real boolean — `arr.length && ...` will render the literal `0` when the array is empty.)

Element variables for cleaner JSX when there are several branches:

```jsx
let button;
if (isLoggedIn) {
  button = <LogoutButton onClick={handleLogout} />;
} else {
  button = <LoginButton onClick={handleLogin} />;
}

return <div>{button}</div>;
```

Returning `null` to render nothing:

```jsx
if (!visible) return null;
```

For more than two or three branches, a lookup object or a small switch helper usually reads better than nested ternaries.

A switching component renders one of several components based on a prop. The cleanest implementation is a lookup object that maps each value to a component.

```jsx
import HomePage from './HomePage';
import AboutPage from './AboutPage';
import FacilitiesPage from './FacilitiesPage';
import ContactPage from './ContactPage';
import HelpPage from './HelpPage';
import PropTypes from 'prop-types';

const PAGES = {
  home: HomePage,
  about: AboutPage,
  facilities: FacilitiesPage,
  contact: ContactPage,
  help: HelpPage,
};

function Page(props) {
  const Handler = PAGES[props.page] || HelpPage;
  return <Handler {...props} />;
}

Page.propTypes = {
  page: PropTypes.oneOf(Object.keys(PAGES)).isRequired,
};

export default Page;
```

How it works:
- The component looked up via `PAGES[props.page]` is assigned to a capitalized local variable (`Handler`); JSX treats lowercase names as HTML tags, so this naming step matters.
- If the prop value doesn't match any key, the component falls back to `HelpPage`.
- The `propTypes` constraint (`oneOf(Object.keys(PAGES))`) catches typos in development.

For URL-driven page switching, React Router with `Routes` and `Route` is usually a better fit; this pattern is most useful when you want to switch based on local state or a non-URL prop.

Listen for the window `resize` event when the component mounts and remove the listener when it unmounts.

Function component with Hooks:

```jsx
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

function WindowSizeDimensions() {
  const [size, setSize] = useState({
    width: window.innerWidth,
    height: window.innerHeight,
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleResize = () =>
      setSize({ width: window.innerWidth, height: window.innerHeight });

    window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
    return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
  }, []);

  return <span>{size.width} x {size.height}</span>;
}
```

Class component equivalent:

```jsx
class WindowSizeDimensions extends React.Component {
  state = { width: window.innerWidth, height: window.innerHeight };

  updateDimension = () => {
    this.setState({ width: window.innerWidth, height: window.innerHeight });
  };

  componentDidMount() {
    window.addEventListener('resize', this.updateDimension);
  }

  componentWillUnmount() {
    window.removeEventListener('resize', this.updateDimension);
  }

  render() {
    return <span>{this.state.width} x {this.state.height}</span>;
  }
}
```

Two things worth noting:
- Always remove the listener in cleanup; otherwise you leak listeners on every mount.
- Resize events fire rapidly. For expensive updates, debounce or throttle the handler (e.g. with lodash's `debounce` or `requestAnimationFrame`).

Two common approaches in React Router v6.

Approach 1: URL parameters

Encode the data in the URL and read it on the other side with `useParams`. This is the cleanest option when the data should be bookmarkable or shareable.

```jsx
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route, Link, useNavigate, useParams } from 'react-router-dom';

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <nav>
        <Link to="/">Home</Link>
        <Link to="/about">About</Link>
      </nav>

      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<HomePage />} />
        <Route path="/about" element={<AboutPage />} />
        <Route path="/about/:aboutId" element={<AboutPage />} />
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}

function HomePage() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  return (
    <button onClick={() => navigate('/about/DemoButton')}>To About</button>
  );
}

function AboutPage() {
  const { aboutId } = useParams();
  if (!aboutId) return <div>No Data Yet</div>;
  return <div>Data from HomePage: {aboutId}</div>;
}
```

Approach 2: Location state

Pass arbitrary data via the second argument to `navigate`, and read it with `useLocation`. The data doesn't appear in the URL, so it survives client-side navigation but not a page reload from a fresh URL.

```jsx
function HomePage() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  return (
    <button onClick={() => navigate('/about', { state: { from: 'HomePage', value: 42 } })}>
      To About
    </button>
  );
}

function AboutPage() {
  const location = useLocation();
  return <div>{JSON.stringify(location.state)}</div>;
}
```

Choose URL params for shareable links and `location.state` for transient data that doesn't belong in the URL.

In React Router v6, render a `<Navigate>` element from your component to declaratively redirect, or call `useNavigate()` to do it imperatively after a side effect.

Declarative redirect with `<Navigate>`:

```jsx
import { Navigate } from 'react-router-dom';

function LoginPage({ isLoggedIn }) {
  if (isLoggedIn) {
    return <Navigate to="/dashboard" replace />;
  }
  return <LoginForm />;
}
```

`replace` swaps the current entry in the history stack instead of pushing a new one, so the user can't use the back button to return to the login screen.

Imperative redirect with `useNavigate`:

```jsx
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

function LoginForm() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();

  const handleSubmit = async (credentials) => {
    await login(credentials);
    navigate('/dashboard', { replace: true });
  };

  return <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>...</form>;
}
```

In older React Router v5 codebases the equivalent was `<Redirect to="...">` or `history.push`; both were renamed in v6 (`<Navigate>` and `useNavigate`).
